What redesign would you propose?
If the billing address is meant to save what the client’s address was at the time of the sale, then keeping it in the Sale table makes sense. But if the billing address is always the same as the client’s address, then those billing fields probably aren’t necessary. In that case, it would be better to just use the address from the Client table to avoid storing the same data twice. Another option would be to create a separate Address table and have both Client and Sale reference it. That would keep all address information in one place and reduce redundancy.

### Task 6 - Explore the Data
Fact (1)
State the fact clearly:
Releases in the database vary significantly in size. The smallest release contains 1 recording, the largest contains 57 recordings, and the average release contains approximately 10 recordings.
Provide SQL evidence:
SELECT 
    MIN(NumRecordings) AS MinRecordings,
    MAX(NumRecordings) AS MaxRecordings,
    AVG(NumRecordings) AS AvgRecordings
FROM (
    SELECT COUNT(*) AS NumRecordings
    FROM Recording
    GROUP BY ReleaseId
) AS t;
+---------------+---------------+---------------+
| MinRecordings | MaxRecordings | AvgRecordings |
+---------------+---------------+---------------+
|             1 |            57 |       10.0951 |
+---------------+---------------+---------------+
Explain why the fact is interesting:
This is interesting because it shows that releases in the database are not all structured the same way. While the average release has about 10 recordings (which sounds like a normal album), some releases are much smaller and some are much larger. The fact that one release has as many as 57 recordings suggests there may be compilation albums, special collections, or bundled content in the database. This suggests the database includes different types of media products, such as singles, full albums, and possibly large collections. It helps give a clearer picture of how the store’s content is structured.

