Fact (3)
State the fact clearly:
Over 85% of all recordings are stored as MPEG audio files, while all other formats individually represent less than 7% of the dataset.
Provide SQL evidence:
SELECT 
    f.Name,
    COUNT(*) AS NumRecordings,
    ROUND(COUNT(*) * 100.0 / (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Recording), 2) AS PercentOfTotal
FROM Recording r
JOIN Format f ON r.FormatId = f.FormatId
GROUP BY f.Name
ORDER BY NumRecordings DESC;
+-----------------------------+---------------+----------------+
| Name                        | NumRecordings | PercentOfTotal |
+-----------------------------+---------------+----------------+
| MPEG audio file             |          3034 |          86.61 |
| Protected AAC audio file    |           237 |           6.77 |
| Protected MPEG-4 video file |           214 |           6.11 |
| AAC audio file              |            11 |           0.31 |
| Purchased AAC audio file    |             7 |           0.20 |
+-----------------------------+---------------+----------------+
Explain why the fact is interesting:
This is interesting because the data is heavily concentrated in one file format. Since over 86% of recordings are MPEG audio files, it suggests the store mainly distributes content in a single standard format. The other formats make up only a small portion of the dataset, which shows they are not a major focus. This supports the idea that the database represents a digital music platform with one dominant distribution type.

